Objective

This study explores the interplay between physical traits and environmental factors in penguins to uncover significant predictors of body mass and interspecies ecological variations. By focusing on measurable characteristics such as flipper length, culmen dimensions, and stable isotope ratios (δ15N, δ13C), the analysis aims to identify key variables influencing body mass. Insights from this study contribute to understanding how ecological factors and specific traits interact to shape body mass patterns across different penguin populations.

  • Anova check for categorical variables
# Extract categorical variables (excluding body_mass itself)
cat_vars <- names(train_df)[sapply(train_df, is.character) & !names(train_df) %in% c("body_mass", "studyname", "individual_id", "clutch_completion", "date_egg")]

# Loop through each categorical variable and perform ANOVA
for (X in cat_vars) {
  cat("\n\n### Relationship between body_mass and", X, "###\n")
  #print(table(train_df[[X]]))  # Print category counts
  
  # Perform ANOVA
  model <- aov(body_mass ~ train_df[[X]], data = train_df)
  #summary(model)  # Print ANOVA results
  print(summary(model))
}

# Perform Chi-square tests between all pairs
for (i in 1:(length(cat_vars)-1)) {
  for (j in (i+1):length(cat_vars)) {
    cat("\nChi-Square Test for", cat_vars[i], "and", cat_vars[j], "\n")
    print(chisq.test(table(train_df[[cat_vars[i]]], train_df[[cat_vars[j]]])))
  }
}

Interpretation of the model

predicted body mass = beta0 + beta1 * flipper_length + beta2 * culmen_depth + beta3 * delta_15N + beta4 * sexMale + beta5 * flipper_length * culmen_depth + beta6 * flipper_length * delta_15N predicted body mass = (-35804.203) + (211.893) * flipper_length + (772.686) * culmen_depth + (2215.682) * delta_15N + (530.152) * sexMale + (-3.931) * flipper_length * culmen_depth + (-12.529) * flipper_length*delta_15N

  • Intercept (-35804.203): The body mass when all continuous predictors are zero and sex is the reference level (FEMALE). This large negative value isn’t directly interpretable since the body mass never reach zero in practice.
  • flipper_length (211.893): For each 1 mm increase in flipper length, body mass increases by approximately 212 grams, holding other variables constant.
  • culmen_depth (772.686): For each 1 mm increase in culmen depth, body mass increases by about 773 grams when other variables are held constant.
  • delta_15_n_o (2215.682): For each unit increase in delta_15_n_o, body mass increases by about 2216 grams, holding other variables constant.
  • sexMALE (530.152): Male penguins are about 530 grams heavier than females on average, controlling for other variables.
  • Interaction terms:

– flipper_length:culmen_depth (-3.931): The effect of flipper length on body mass decreases by about 3.9 grams for each 1 mm increase in culmen depth.

– flipper_length:delta_15_n_o (-12.529): The effect of flipper length on body mass decreases by about 12.5 grams for each unit increase in delta_15_n_o.

All predictors are highly significant (p < 0.01), with most having p-values well below 0.001.

model is the best model based on the following: AIC: 3709.37 Adj. R^2: 0.8587 p-value: <2.2e-16 F-statistic:262.4 on df 6

test <- read.csv("test_penguins.csv")
colnames(test)<- c("studyname","sample_number","species","island","individual_id","clutch_completion","date_egg","culmen_length","culmen_depth","flipper_length","body_mass","sex","delta_15_n_o","delta_13_c_o")

test$pred_mass <- (predict(model_bc, newdata = test))^(1/0.75)
# test$pred_mass <- test$pred_mass
test$residuals <- test$body_mass - test$pred_mass

rmse <- sqrt(mean(test$residuals)^2)

mae <- mean(abs(test$residuals))

sst <- sum((test$body_mass - mean(test$body_mass))^2)
sse <- sum((test$residuals)^2)
r_squared <- 1 - (sse / sst)

cat("\n### Testing Data ###\n")

  • RMSE (53.92): On average, the model’s predictions deviate from actual body_mass values by about 53.92 units (grams).
  • MAE (222.1): The absolute error in predictions is 222.1 units on average.
  • R² (0.874 or 87.4%): The model explains 87.4% of the variability in body mass using the predictor variables. This indicates a strong fit in the training data.

Conclusion

  • Better performance on test data: The lower RMSE (55.92) in the test dataset suggests that the test set has less variance or that the model handles unseen data well.
  • No major overfitting or underfitting issues: If R² had dropped significantly in the test data, it would indicate overfitting. But in this case, model show strong predictive power.
  • The model appears robust and well-generalized, making accurate predictions across both dataset.
  • The developed model successfully identifies significant predictors and can be used for ecological studies or conservation planning to understand body mass variations across penguin populations.
